# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-digital-twin
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] A **digital twin** is a computational model of an intended or actual real-world physical product, system, or process (a *physical twin*) that serves as a digital counterpart of it for purposes such as simulation, integration, testing, monitoring, and maintenance.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] By its strict definition, a digital twin is distinguished from an ordinary simulation in that it continuously uses real data from its physical counterpart to dynamically synchronize with the real system.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] A model that operates without data from its physical counterpart may also be described as a digital twin, but this is considered an overly broad and largely marketing-oriented interpretation of the concept.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] A digital twin is "a set of adaptive models that emulate the behaviour of a physical system in a virtual system getting real-time data to update itself along its life cycle.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twins emerged through continual improvements in modeling and engineering.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] In the 2010s and 2020s, manufacturing industries began moving beyond digital product definition to extending the digital twin concept to the entire manufacturing process.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Doing so allows the benefits of virtualization to be extended to domains such as inventory management including lean manufacturing, machinery crash avoidance, tooling design, troubleshooting, and preventive maintenance.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twinning therefore allows extended reality and spatial computing to be applied not just to the product itself but also to all of the business processes that contribute to its production.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] The first digital twin, although not labeled as such, came about at NASA during the 1960s as a means of modelling the Apollo missions.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] NASA used simulators to evaluate the failure of Apollo 13's oxygen tanks.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] The broader idea that became the digital twin concept was anticipated by David Gelernter's 1991 book *Mirror Worlds*.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] During the late 1990s, the emergence of digital cities provided early practical demonstrations of this concept at an urban scale.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Projects such as "Helsinki Arena 2000" (initiated in 1996) built interactive 3D virtual models of the physical city.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] The digital twin concept consists of three distinct parts: the physical object or process and its physical environment, the digital representation of the object or process, and the communication channel between the physical and virtual representations.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] The connections between the physical version and the digital version include information flows and data that includes physical sensor flows between the physical and virtual objects and environments.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] The communication connection is referred to as the digital thread.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] The International Council of Systems Engineers (INCOSE) maintains in its Systems Engineering Body of Knowledge (SEBoK) that: "A digital twin is a related yet distinct concept to digital engineering.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twins are commonly divided into the three subtypes: *digital twin prototype* (DTP), *digital twin instance* (DTI), and *digital twin aggregate* (DTA).
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] The DTP consists of the designs, analyses, and processes that realize a physical product.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] The DTI is the digital twin of each individual instance of the product once it is manufactured.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] The DTI is linked with its physical counterpart for the remainder of the physical counterpart's life.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] The DTA is the aggregation of DTIs whose data and information can be used for interrogation about the physical product, prognostics, and learning.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] The specific information contained in the digital twins is driven by use cases.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] The digital twin is a logical construct, meaning that the actual data and information may be contained in other applications.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] For some types of digital twin, there is contention about whether the label truly applies.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] For example, LNS Research defines "digital twin" as any executable virtual model of a physical system.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Researchers at the National Physical Laboratory have contested this definition, arguing that this includes "plain" models that do not produce results equivalent to measured quantities or are not dynamically updated in accordance with those measurements.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] They argue that this overly broad definition risks causing potential users to view "digital twin" as a buzzword and become cynical toward the idea.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] The term has also been applied to large language models trained to mimic specific people.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Describing these as "digital twins" implies a level of comprehensive fidelity that they fail to live up to in practice, and can cause psychological harm to users who believe that the model preserves or replicates human identity.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] In 2019 Sheremetyevo International Airport started developing and implementation of a digital twin model aimed to forecast and plan all the airport operations.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] In the design phase, a Digital Twin Prototype (DTP) is often created before a physical product exists.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] This virtual model is used for extensive simulation to test design choices and manufacturing processes.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] For example, in virtual commissioning, a digital twin of a proposed production line can simulate its operation to identify bottlenecks, optimize the layout of machinery, and validate automation logic before any physical equipment is installed.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] During production, digital twins use data from sensors connected to manufacturing equipment via the Internet of Things (IoT) to monitor and optimize operations.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] A distinction is sometimes made between a Digital Shadow, where data flows one way from the physical asset to the digital model, and a true Digital Twin, where the data flow is bidirectional, allowing the twin to also send control commands back to the asset.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Applications in this phase include process monitoring and control, where sensors measuring force, temperature, vibration, or power consumption feed data to a digital twin to monitor a process in real time.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] In friction stir welding, for instance, force sensor data can indicate whether sufficient contact is being made between the tool and workpieces to ensure a quality weld.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] In machining, acoustic emission signals can be analyzed to differentiate a worn tool from a new one, allowing for automated quality control.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Another application is real-time quality inspection, where vision systems integrated with a digital twin can automatically inspect products for defects on the production line.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] These systems can process images to detect surface defects, such as cracks or porosity in a weld, or measure geometric dimensions to ensure they meet specifications.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] After a product is manufactured and in service, its digital twin continues to collect performance data, often referred to as a Digital Twin Instance (DTI).
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] This is particularly valuable for high-value industrial assets like jet engines, wind turbines, or industrial machinery.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] One key application is predictive maintenance, where the digital twin analyzes operational data (e.g., temperature, vibration) to predict when a component is likely to fail.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] For example, a gearbox twin can analyze vibration signals to detect the future breakage of a tooth.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] This allows maintenance to be scheduled proactively, reducing unplanned downtime and preventing catastrophic failures.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Another application is performance optimization.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] By aggregating data from a whole fleet of assets—a Digital Twin Aggregate (DTA)—manufacturers can understand how their products perform under different real-world conditions.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] This information can be used to provide operational guidance to users or to inform the design of future product generations, creating a closed feedback loop from the service phase back to the design phase.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twins are transforming construction by creating dynamic digital replicas of physical assets.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] They support health monitoring, ergonomic risk assessment, and predictive maintenance of structures like bridges and historical buildings.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Applications also optimize building energy and carbon performance.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Case studies, such as Weihai Port, highlight their practical success.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twins rely on robust system architectures and tailored, requirements-driven designs.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Advanced models like LSTM enable predictive capabilities, though challenges in integration and scaling remain.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Recent studies have emphasized their role in enabling real-time operational control of HVAC, lighting, shading, and renewable systems, contributing significantly to decarbonization strategies.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Layered system architectures typically comprising sensing, data processing, simulation, and visualization layers that support scalable and interoperable solutions for these applications.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Geographic digital twins have been popularised in urban planning practice, given the increasing appetite for digital technology in the Smart Cities movement.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] These digital twins are often proposed in the form of interactive platforms to capture and display real-time 3D and 4D spatial data in order to model urban environments (cities) and the data feeds within them.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Visualization technologies such as augmented reality (AR) systems are being used as both collaborative tools for design and planning in the built environment integrating data feeds from embedded sensors in cities and API services to form digital twins.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] For example, AR can be used to create augmented reality maps, buildings, and data feeds projected onto tabletops for collaborative viewing by built environment professionals.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] In the United Kingdom in November 2018, for example, the Centre for Digital Built Britain published *The Gemini Principles*, outlining principles to guide development of a "national digital twin".
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] One of the earliest examples of a working 'digital twin' was achieved in 1996 during construction of the Heathrow Express facilities at Heathrow Airport's Terminal 1.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Consultant Mott MacDonald and BIM pioneer Jonathan Ingram connected movement sensors in the cofferdam and boreholes to the digital object-model to display movements in the model.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] A digital grouting object was made to monitor the effects of pumping grout into the earth to stabilise ground movements.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Healthcare has been recognized as an industry being disrupted by the digital twin technology.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] The concept was originally proposed and first used in health care product or equipment prognostics.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] With a digital twin, it has been predicted that lives could be improved in terms of medical health, sports and education by taking a more data-driven approach to healthcare.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Personalized models for patients, continuously adjustable based on tracked health and lifestyle parameters could ultimately lead to a virtual patient, with detailed description of the healthy state of an individual and not only on previous records.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Furthermore, the digital twin could enable individual's records to be compared to the population in order to easier find patterns with great detail.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] The biggest benefit of the digital twin on the healthcare industry would be the fact that healthcare could be tailored to anticipate the responses of individual patients.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twins have been expected not only to lead to better resolutions when defining the health of an individual but also change the expected image of a healthy person.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Previously, 'healthy' was seen as the absence of disease indications.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Now, 'healthy' patients can be compared to the rest of the population in order to really define healthy.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] However, the emergence of the digital twin in healthcare also may lead to inequality, as the technology might not be accessible for everyone by widening the gap between the rich and poor.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Furthermore, the digital twin will identify patterns in a population which may lead to discrimination.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] As of 2025, digital twin applications in healthcare have expanded to include real‑time AI‑driven patient monitoring systems, personalized surgical simulations, and predictive diagnostics using multimodal data (e.g. imaging + wearables).
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twins in the automobile industry are implemented by using existing data in order to facilitate processes and reduce marginal costs.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Currently, automobile designers expand the existing physical materiality by incorporating software-based digital abilities.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] A specific example of digital twin technology in the automotive industry is where automotive engineers use digital twin technology in combination with the firm's analytical tool in order to analyze how a specific car is driven.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] In doing so, they can suggest incorporating new features in the car that can reduce car accidents on the road, which was previously not possible in such a short time frame.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twins are increasingly employed in the renewable energy industry to monitor and optimize systems such as wind farms, solar installations, microgrids, and battery storage.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] These virtual models help operators simulate real-world conditions, forecast issues, and enhance operational efficiency in a low-risk environment.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Recent reviews emphasize that digital twins support advanced management strategies for microgrids, such as day-ahead scheduling and real-time coordination across renewable assets, enhancing grid resilience.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Systematic analysis further shows that combining digital twins with predictive analytics in smart energy systems can reduce energy consumption by up to 30%, thanks to optimized load balancing and proactive maintenance.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] A UK-based demonstrator project used a digital twin for voltage control simulations in a microgrid, showing a reduction of renewable curtailment by approximately 56% in typical operation.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Utilities and technology providers worldwide are now piloting twin platforms to anticipate turbine maintenance, improve battery storage usage, and simulate grid behavior under extreme or variable conditions, indicating a trend toward more automated and resilient energy systems.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Digital twin technology is used in heritage and archaeological contexts to anticipate heritage loss and ensuring that an accurate record exists for heritage assets at risk, and engaging with planners to anticipate the needs of the cultural heritage sector.
[src:network-digital-twin/digital-twin] Twins can also be drivers for tourism and urban heritage trails, where they can act as introductions to significant or iconic monuments, thereby using heritage to draw people into urban centres.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] A **discrete-event simulation** (**DES**) models the operation of a system as a (discrete) sequence of events in time.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Each event occurs at a particular instant in time and marks a change of state in the system.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Between consecutive events, no change in the system is assumed to occur; thus the simulation time can directly jump to the occurrence time of the next event, which is called **next-event time progression**.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] In addition to next-event time progression, there is also an alternative approach, called **incremental time progression**, where time is broken up into small time slices and the system state is updated according to the set of events/activities happening in the time slice.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Because not every time slice has to be simulated, a next-event time simulation can typically run faster than a corresponding incremental time simulation.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Both forms of DES contrast with continuous simulation in which the system state is changed continuously over time on the basis of a set of differential equations defining the rates of change for state variables.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] In the past, these three types of simulation have also been referred to, respectively, as: event scheduling simulation, activity scanning simulation, and process interaction simulation.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] It can also be noted that there are similarities between the implementation of the event queue in event scheduling, and the scheduling queue used in operating systems.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] A common exercise in learning how to build discrete-event simulations is to model a queueing system, such as customers arriving at a bank teller to be served by a clerk.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] In this example, the system objects are ***customer*** and ***teller***, while the system events are ***customer-arrival***, ***service-start*** and ***service-end***.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] When a *service-start* event occurs, the state variable *teller-status* is set to "busy" and a *service-end* follow-up event is scheduled with a delay (obtained from sampling a *service-time* random variable).
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] When a *service-end* event occurs, the state variable *queue-length* is decremented by 1 (representing the customer's departure).
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] If the state variable *queue-length* is still greater than zero, a *Service-Start* follow-up event is scheduled to happen without any delay.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Otherwise, the state variable *teller-status* is set to "available".
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] The random variables that need to be characterized to model this system stochastically are the *interarrival-time* for recurrent *customer-arrival* events and the *service-time* for the delays of *service-end* events.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] A system state is a set of variables that captures the salient properties of the system to be studied.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] The state trajectory over time S(t) can be mathematically represented by a step function whose value can change whenever an event occurs.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] The simulation must keep track of the current simulation time, in whatever measurement units are suitable for the system being modeled.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] In discrete-event simulations, as opposed to continuous simulations, time 'hops' because events are instantaneous – the clock skips to the next event start time as the simulation proceeds.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] The simulation maintains at least one list of simulation events.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] This is sometimes called the *pending event set* because it lists events that are pending as a result of previously simulated event but have yet to be simulated themselves.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] An event is described by the time at which it occurs and a type, indicating the code that will be used to simulate that event.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] It is common for the event code to be parametrized, in which case, the event description also contains parameters to the event code.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] The event list is also referred to as the *future event list* (FEL) or *future event set* (FES).
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] When events are instantaneous, activities that extend over time are modeled as sequences of events.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Some simulation frameworks allow the time of an event to be specified as an interval, giving the start time and the end time of each event.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Single-threaded simulation engines based on instantaneous events have just one current event.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] In contrast, multi-threaded simulation engines and simulation engines supporting an interval-based event model may have multiple current events.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] In both cases, there are significant problems with synchronization between current events.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] The pending event set is typically organized as a priority queue, sorted by event time.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] That is, regardless of the order in which events are added to the event set, they are removed in strictly chronological order.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Various priority queue implementations have been studied in the context of discrete event simulation; alternatives studied have included splay trees, skip lists, calendar queues, and ladder queues.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] On massively-parallel machines, such as multi-core or many-core CPUs, the pending event set can be implemented by relying on non-blocking algorithms, in order to reduce the cost of synchronization among the concurrent threads.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Typically, events are scheduled dynamically as the simulation proceeds.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] For example, in the bank example noted above, the event CUSTOMER-ARRIVAL at time t would, if the CUSTOMER_QUEUE was empty and TELLER was idle, include the creation of the subsequent event CUSTOMER-DEPARTURE to occur at time t+s, where s is a number generated from the SERVICE-TIME distribution.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] The simulation needs to generate random variables of various kinds, depending on the system model.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] This is accomplished by one or more Pseudorandom number generators.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] The use of pseudo-random numbers as opposed to true random numbers is a benefit should a simulation need a rerun with exactly the same behavior.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] One of the problems with the random number distributions used in discrete-event simulation is that the steady-state distributions of event times may not be known in advance.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] As a result, the initial set of events placed into the pending event set will not have arrival times representative of the steady-state distribution.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] This problem is typically solved by bootstrapping the simulation model.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Only a limited effort is made to assign realistic times to the initial set of pending events.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] These events, however, schedule additional events, and with time, the distribution of event times approaches its steady state.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] This is called *bootstrapping* the simulation model.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] In gathering statistics from the running model, it is important to either disregard events that occur before the steady state is reached or to run the simulation for long enough that the bootstrapping behavior is overwhelmed by steady-state behavior.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] (This use of the term *bootstrapping* can be contrasted with its use in both statistics and computing).
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] The simulation typically keeps track of the system's statistics, which quantify the aspects of interest.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] In the bank example, it is of interest to track the mean waiting times.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] In a simulation model, performance metrics are not analytically derived from probability distributions, but rather as averages over replications, that is different runs of the model.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Confidence intervals are usually constructed to help assess the quality of the output.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Because events are bootstrapped, theoretically a discrete-event simulation could run forever.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] So the simulation designer must decide when the simulation will end.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Typical choices are "at time t" or "after processing n number of events" or, more generally, "when statistical measure X reaches the value x".
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Pidd (1998) has proposed the three-phased approach to discrete event simulation.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] In this approach, the first phase is to jump to the next chronological event.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] The second phase is to execute all events that unconditionally occur at that time (these are called B-events).
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] The third phase is to execute all events that conditionally occur at that time (these are called C-events).
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] The three phase approach is a refinement of the event-based approach in which simultaneous events are ordered so as to make the most efficient use of computer resources.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] The three-phase approach is used by a number of commercial simulation software packages, but from the user's point of view, the specifics of the underlying simulation method are generally hidden.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Simulation approaches are particularly well equipped to help users diagnose issues in complex environments.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] The theory of constraints illustrates the importance of understanding bottlenecks in a system.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Identifying and removing bottlenecks allows improving processes and the overall system.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] For instance, in manufacturing enterprises bottlenecks may be created by excess inventory, overproduction, variability in processes and variability in routing or sequencing.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] By accurately documenting the system with the help of a simulation model it is possible to gain a bird’s eye view of the entire system.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] A working model of a system allows management to understand performance drivers.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] A simulation can be built to include any number of performance indicators such as worker utilization, on-time delivery rate, scrap rate, cash cycles, and so on.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] An operating theater is generally shared between several surgical disciplines.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Through better understanding the nature of these procedures it may be possible to increase the patient throughput.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Example: If a heart surgery takes on average four hours, changing an operating room schedule from eight available hours to nine will not increase patient throughput.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] On the other hand, if a hernia procedure takes on average twenty minutes providing an extra hour may also not yield any increased throughput if the capacity and average time spent in the recovery room is not considered.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Many systems improvement ideas are built on sound principles, proven methodologies (Lean, Six Sigma, TQM, etc.) yet fail to improve the overall system.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] A simulation model allows the user to understand and test a performance improvement idea in the context of the overall system.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Simulation modeling is commonly used to model potential investments.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Through modeling investments decision-makers can make informed decisions and evaluate potential alternatives.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] Discrete event simulation is used in computer network to simulate new protocols, different system architectures (distributed, hierarchical, centralised, P2P) before actual deployment.
[src:network-digital-twin/discrete-event-simulation] It is possible to define different evaluation metrics, such as service time, bandwidth, dropped packets, resource consumption, and so on.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] In computer science, **model checking** or **property checking** is a method for checking whether a finite-state model of a system meets a given specification (also known as correctness).
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] This is typically associated with hardware or software systems, where the specification contains liveness requirements (such as avoidance of livelock) as well as safety requirements (such as avoidance of states representing a system crash).
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] In order to solve such a problem algorithmically, both the model of the system and its specification are formulated in some precise mathematical language.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] To this end, the problem is formulated as a task in logic, namely to check whether a structure satisfies a given logical formula.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] This general concept applies to many kinds of logic and many kinds of structures.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] A simple model-checking problem consists of verifying whether a formula in the propositional logic is satisfied by a given structure.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Property checking is used for verification when two descriptions are not equivalent.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] During refinement, the specification is complemented with details that are unnecessary in the higher-level specification.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] There is no need to verify the newly introduced properties against the original specification since this is not possible.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Therefore, the strict bi-directional equivalence check is relaxed to a one-way property check.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] The implementation or design is regarded as a model of the system, whereas the specifications are properties that the model must satisfy.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] An important class of model-checking methods has been developed for checking models of hardware and software designs where the specification is given by a temporal logic formula.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Pioneering work in temporal logic specification was done by Amir Pnueli, who received the 1996 Turing award for "seminal work introducing temporal logic into computing science".
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Model checking began with the pioneering work of E.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Clarke, Emerson, and Sifakis shared the 2007 Turing Award for their seminal work founding and developing the field of model checking.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Model checking is most often applied to hardware designs.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] For software, because of undecidability (see computability theory) the approach cannot be fully algorithmic, apply to all systems, and always give an answer; in the general case, it may fail to prove or disprove a given property.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] In embedded-systems hardware, it is possible to validate a specification delivered, e.g., by means of UML activity diagrams or control-interpreted Petri nets.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] The structure is usually given as a source code description in an industrial hardware description language or a special-purpose language.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Such a program corresponds to a finite-state machine (FSM), i.e., a directed graph consisting of nodes (or vertices) and edges.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] A set of atomic propositions is associated with each node, typically stating which memory elements are one.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] The nodes represent states of a system, the edges represent possible transitions that may alter the state, while the atomic propositions represent the basic properties that hold at a point of execution.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Formally, the problem can be stated as follows: given a desired property, expressed as a temporal logic formula p , and a structure M with initial state s , decide if $M,s\models p$ .
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] If M is finite, as it is in hardware, model checking reduces to a graph search.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Instead of enumerating reachable states one at a time, the state space can sometimes be traversed more efficiently by considering large numbers of states at a single step.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] When such state-space traversal is based on representations of a set of states and transition relations as logical formulas, binary decision diagrams (BDD) or other related data structures, the model-checking method is *symbolic*.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Historically, the first symbolic methods used BDDs.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] After the success of propositional satisfiability in solving the planning problem in artificial intelligence (see satplan) in 1996, the same approach was generalized to model checking for linear temporal logic (LTL): the planning problem corresponds to model checking for safety properties.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] This method is known as bounded model checking.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] The success of Boolean satisfiability solvers in bounded model checking led to the widespread use of satisfiability solvers in symbolic model checking.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] One example of such a system requirement: *Between the time an elevator is called at a floor and the time it opens its doors at that floor, the elevator can arrive at that floor at most twice*.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Here, $\Box$ should be read as "always", $\Diamond$ as "eventually", ${\mathcal {U}}$ as "until" and the other symbols are standard logical symbols, $\lor$ for "or", $\land$ for "and" and $\lnot$ for "not".
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Model-checking tools face a combinatorial blow up of the state-space, commonly known as the state explosion problem, that must be addressed to solve most real-world problems.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] There are several approaches to combat this problem.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Bounded model-checking algorithms unroll the FSM for a fixed number of steps, k , and check whether a property violation can occur in k or fewer steps.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] This typically involves encoding the restricted model as an instance of SAT.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] The process can be repeated with larger and larger values of k until all possible violations have been ruled out (cf.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Iterative deepening depth-first search).
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Abstraction attempts to prove properties of a system by first simplifying it.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] The simplified system usually does not satisfy exactly the same properties as the original one so that a process of refinement may be necessary.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Generally, one requires the abstraction to be *sound* (the properties proved on the abstraction are true of the original system); however, sometimes the abstraction is not *complete* (not all true properties of the original system are true of the abstraction).
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] An example of abstraction is to ignore the values of non-Boolean variables and to only consider Boolean variables and the control flow of the program; such an abstraction, though it may appear coarse, may, in fact, be sufficient to prove e.g. properties of mutual exclusion.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Counterexample-guided abstraction refinement (CEGAR) begins checking with a coarse (i.e. imprecise) abstraction and iteratively refines it.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] When a violation (i.e. counterexample) is found, the tool analyzes it for feasibility (i.e., is the violation genuine or the result of an incomplete abstraction?).
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] If the violation is feasible, it is reported to the user.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] If it is not, the proof of infeasibility is used to refine the abstraction and checking begins again.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Model-checking tools were initially developed to reason about the logical correctness of discrete state systems, but have since been extended to deal with real-time and limited forms of hybrid systems.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] Model checking is also studied in the field of computational complexity theory.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] This problem is in the circuit class **AC0**.
[src:network-digital-twin/model-checking] These results have been extended to the task of enumerating all solutions to a first-order formula with free variables.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-management] A number of applications and protocols exist to support network and network device management.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-management] Network management allows IT professionals to monitor network components within a large network area.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-management] Access methods include the SNMP, command-line interface (CLI), custom XML, CMIP, Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI), Transaction Language 1 (TL1), CORBA, NETCONF, RESTCONF and the Java Management Extensions (JMX).
[src:network-digital-twin/network-management] Schemas include the Structure of Management Information (SMI), YANG, WBEM, the Common Information Model (CIM Schema), and MTOSI amongst others.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-management] Effective network management can provide positive strategic impacts.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-management] For example, in the case of developing an infrastructure, providing participants with some interactive space allows them to collaborate with each other, thereby promoting overall benefits.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-management] At the same time, the value of network management to the strategic network is also affected by the relationship between participants.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-management] Active participation, interaction and collaboration can make them more trusting of each other and enhance cohesion.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] There are many different ways to measure the performance of a network, as each network is different in nature and design.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] Performance can also be modeled and simulated instead of measured; one example of this is using state transition diagrams to model queuing performance or to use a Network Simulator.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] The available channel bandwidth and achievable signal-to-noise ratio determine the maximum possible throughput.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] It is not generally possible to send more data than dictated by the Shannon-Hartley Theorem.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] The *Time Window* is the period over which the throughput is measured.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] The choice of an appropriate time window will often dominate calculations of throughput, and whether latency is taken into account or not will determine whether the latency affects the throughput or not.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] The speed of light imposes a minimum propagation time on all electromagnetic signals.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] where s is the distance and cm is the speed of light in the medium (roughly 200,000 km/s for most fiber or electrical media, depending on their velocity factor).
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] This approximately means an additional millisecond round-trip delay (RTT) per 100 km (or 62 miles) of distance between hosts.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] Other delays also occur in intermediate nodes.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] In packet switched networks delays can occur due to queueing.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] In digital transmission, the number of **bit errors** is the number of received bits of a data stream over a communication channel that have been altered due to noise, interference, distortion or bit synchronization errors.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] The **bit error rate** or **bit error ratio** (**BER**) is the number of bit errors divided by the total number of transferred bits during a studied time interval.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] BER is a unitless performance measure, often expressed as a percentage.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] The **bit error probability** *pe* is the expectation value of the BER.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] The BER can be considered as an approximate estimate of the bit error probability.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] This estimate is accurate for a long time interval and a high number of bit errors.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] All of the factors above, coupled with user requirements and user perceptions, play a role in determining the perceived 'fastness' or utility, of a network connection.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] The relationship between throughput, latency, and user experience is most aptly understood in the context of a shared network medium, and as a scheduling problem.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] For some systems, latency and throughput are coupled entities.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] In TCP/IP, latency can also directly affect throughput.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] In TCP connections, the large bandwidth-delay product of high latency connections, combined with relatively small TCP window sizes on many devices, effectively causes the throughput of a high latency connection to drop sharply with latency.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] This can be remedied with various techniques, such as increasing the TCP congestion window size, or more drastic solutions, such as packet coalescing, TCP acceleration, and forward error correction, all of which are commonly used for high latency satellite links.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] TCP acceleration converts the TCP packets into a stream that is similar to UDP.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] Because of this, the TCP acceleration software must provide its own mechanisms to ensure the reliability of the link, taking the latency and bandwidth of the link into account, and both ends of the high latency link must support the method used.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] In the Media Access Control (MAC) layer, performance issues such as throughput and end-to-end delay are also addressed.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] Many systems can be characterized as dominated either by throughput limitations or by latency limitations in terms of end-user utility or experience.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] In some cases, hard limits such as the speed of light present unique problems to such systems and nothing can be done to correct this.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] Other systems allow for significant balancing and optimization for best user experience.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] A telecom satellite in geosynchronous orbit imposes a path length of at least 71000 km between transmitter and receiver. which means a minimum delay between message request and message receipt, or latency of 473 ms.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] This delay can be very noticeable and affects satellite phone service regardless of available throughput capacity.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] These long path length considerations are exacerbated when communicating with space probes and other long-range targets beyond Earth's atmosphere.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] The Deep Space Network implemented by NASA is one such system that must cope with these problems.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] Largely latency driven, the GAO has criticized the current architecture.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] Several different methods have been proposed to handle the intermittent connectivity and long delays between packets, such as delay-tolerant networking.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] At interstellar distances, the difficulties in designing radio systems that can achieve any throughput at all are massive.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] In these cases, maintaining communication is a bigger issue than how long that communication takes.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-performance] Transportation is concerned almost entirely with throughput, which is why physical deliveries of backup tape archives are still largely done by vehicle.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] In computer network research, **network simulation** is a technique whereby a software program replicates the behavior of a real network.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] This is achieved by calculating the interactions between the different network entities such as routers, switches, nodes, access points, links, etc.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] Most simulators use discrete event simulation in which the modeling of systems in which state variables change at discrete points in time.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] The behavior of the network and the various applications and services it supports can then be observed in a test lab; various attributes of the environment can also be modified in a controlled manner to assess how the network/protocols would behave under different conditions.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] A **network simulator** is a software program that can predict the performance of a computer network or a wireless communication network.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] Since communication networks have become too complex for traditional analytical methods to provide an accurate understanding of system behavior, network simulators are used.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] In simulators, the computer network is modeled with devices, links, applications, etc., and the network performance is reported.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] Most of the commercial simulators are GUI driven, while open source network simulators are CLI driven.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] The network model/configuration describes the network (nodes, routers, switches, links) and the events (data transmissions, packet error, etc.).
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] Output results would include network-level metrics, link metrics, device metrics etc.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] Further, drill down in terms of simulations trace files would also be available.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] Trace files log every packet, every event that occurred in the simulation and is used for analysis.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] Network emulation allows users to introduce real devices and applications into a test network (simulated) that alters packet flow in such a way as to mimic the behavior of a live network.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] Live traffic can pass through the simulator and be affected by objects within the simulation.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] The typical methodology is that real packets from a live application are sent to the emulation server (where the virtual network is simulated).
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] The real packet gets 'modulated' into a simulation packet.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] The simulation packet gets demodulated into a real packet after experiencing effects of loss, errors, delay, jitter etc., thereby transferring these network effects into the real packet.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] Thus it is as-if the real packet flowed through a real network but in reality it flowed through the simulated network.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] Emulation is widely used in the design stage for validating communication networks prior to deployment.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] There are both free/open-source and proprietary network simulators available.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] There are also some notable commercial network simulators such as OPNET and NetSim.
[src:network-digital-twin/network-simulation] There are a wide variety of network simulators, ranging from the very simple to the very complex.
